post_text:
If you're wondering what school is going to look like in the fall, you are certainly not alone. That picture for the future is going to change many times between now and then, and our questions and concerns will be met with evolving answers and solutions. Here is where we are today. Please take the time to view and share the message and video below from Superintendent Steve Edwards. Go Rocket City!

From Steve:

Whether I'm walking around Rocket City, shopping at Meijer, sitting at my desk, or even out of the district, the following question has been posed to me hundreds of times:

"Steve, what will school look like in the fall?"

I was on page four of a letter that rambled.... and thought a video might make more sense. The link below is a 12 minute video that explains where we are in the process.

https://youtu.be/eFlLLUxWm_M

Stay well, have a great weekend, and Go Rockets!

Sincerely,

Steve

post_text:
Here's a question everyone has heard at a cocktail party: If you were on a deserted island and could only have one movie to watch over and over, what would it be? Not sure where the electricity was coming from on the deserted island, but that's not important.

Let's put a contemporary twist on that question, since we are spending so much time in/on our own little islands. What are your three favorite movies of all time? Feel free to share them here, and be sure to ask your kiddos the same question. Stay healthy, stay happy, and Go Rocket City!

post_text:
Make it a game night!
As we all adjust to the new world order ushered in by the Coronavirus, there are lots of opportunities to continue learning - and to have fun! Here is one recommendation from R-P Director of Teaching and Learning, Nate Smith:
"Play board, card, and strategy games - they all support numerical thinking, problem solving, and working together."
Enjoy one another, and enjoy the opportunity to learn and play together. Go Rocket City!

YOUTUBE.COM
Getting Started With Trauma-Informed Practices

Rocketoons
June 28, 2019 at 2:25 PM ·

“If you’re fearful, if you’re anxious, if you’re distracted by something that has happened to you, you literally can’t learn. Your brain shuts down. So it’s essential to give kids social and emotional tools to recover from the challenges they have experienced.

Take actual classroom time to work on the building blocks of how to perceive your emotions, how to talk about them, how to get along with other people, how to take a moment and become calm when you need to, how to express your needs so that others can meet them.”

Dr. Linda Darling-Hammond
President and CEO
Learning Policy Institute
“How Learning Happens: Getting Started With Trauma-Informed Practices”
https://youtu.be/eWIV3wWygS4

Just in case you didn't see the email this morning, here is a request from Steve Edwards. Please spread the word.

Good morning Rockets,

You may or may not know that today was supposed to be "student count day." It is a day that the state uses to help determine funding for each school. Because of the snow day, count day has been moved to tomorrow, Thursday, February 14. We are aware that some will be missing due to plans to extend mid-winter break. If your son or daughter is going to be missing for any reason tomorrow, PLEASE do us a favor and call in to your child's school to report the absence. When absences are "reported" by parents, it gives us a window of time to still count them as students.

Thanks a ton for your help with this.

Sincerely,

Steve

Steve Edwards

Superintendent, Reeths-Puffer Schools

Ask and you shall receive! After yesterday's Episode One post we had a few inquiries basically asking to know more about Rocketoons, so here's a little overview:
1. They are free for everyone to use throughout the United States and Canada.
2. They are made right here in Rocket City.
3. Each episode comes with a Cartoonversation Card so teachers, parents, and kids can talk together about the topics.
4. For teachers, RP's very own Terri Portice has helped align state teaching standards for grades 1-12 (they are all available at rocketoons.com).
5. Speaking of rocketoons.com, that's all you need to watch the toons.
6. We'll share a trailer every day, so here is Episode Two: Moving To A New School.
7. Feel free to share this news with anyone and everyone so they can enjoy Rocketoons as well.
8. Go Rocket City!

post_text: It doesn't take long to get used to snow days. Getting enough sleep to get back into the swing of things? Maybe that takes a little more effort. Now is a good time to visit Rocket City's very own Rocketoons. Episode One is all about getting enough sleep and keeping the schedule from getting too cluttered. Here's the trailer, and you can watch the full episode at rocketoons.com - all you have to do is click on Watch Now and then enter your county as your password. Don't forget the Cartoonversation™ Card (available for each episode), so you can have a chat with your young Rocket(s) and learn a thing or two about getting enough rest. Go Rocket City! Better yet - Go Get a Good Night's Sleep, Rocket City!

Feel free to spread the word! Another great reason to love Rocket City, and a great opportunity to help neighbors in need. This was sent out as part of an email from Steve Edwards earlier today:

A group of volunteers has collaborated to offer assistance to those who might be in some type of food emergency during this challenging time.

Families in the RP community in need of immediate food assistance may contact:

FoodAssistRP@gmail.com

or

Text 231-220-4095

Send your phone number, delivery address and number of people in your household.

We hope to make deliveries this afternoon/evening. Basics such as bread, peanut butter, apples or salad.

Thanks for your continued patience and thanks to this generous group of volunteers for helping out Rocket City!

Yesterday we shared a list of items you should have in your car during snowmageddon, so today (courtesy of the Detroit Free Press), let's share some items you should NOT have in your car when the mercury drops. Feel free to read the article in full by clicking on the link below the list. Also, a special thanks to Lea Markowski who shared yesterday's post along with her own suggestions for adding to the winter safety kit!
Here are the eight no-no's from the Free Press:
1. Cell phones
2. Soda/beer
3. Musical instruments
4. Eggs
5. Canned foods
6. Medication
7. Loved ones (let's hope this list isn't in order of importance!)
8. A low gas tank

https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/01/02/cold-weather-car/995178001

post_text:
Most of us have been watching the weather, and it looks like that is going to be the case a few more times at least. To keep up with Mother Nature, here's a good snow day activity: check your winter safety items that are in your car. Lifehacker.com lists 30 items. USA Today lists 11 items. Popular Mechanics lists seven items. We'll go with Business Insider who honors the classical top ten list:
1. A portable charger for your phone
2. Jumper cables
3. A blanket (or two)
4. Road flares
5. Flashlight (check those batteries!)
6. Emergency escape tool (for breaking windows and cutting seat belts)
7. Shovel
8. First aid kit
9. Rock salt
10. AAA-approved emergency kit (which likely has several of these items)

Stay safe, stay warm, and Go Rocket City!

Did you know that drowning is the #1 cause of accidental death for children (other than traffic accidents)? Did you know that Lake Michigan’s swift currents make it the deadliest Great Lake?

Here’s the good news: Every third grader in the Reeths-Puffer district has the benefit of learning water safety through the Muskegon YMCA Safety Around Water program. It costs the Y $58 per child to teach this 5 week program - we pay just $5 per child.

Join us at a breakfast benefit to help the Muskegon YMCA continue this life-saving program for our kids.

When: Tuesday June 12th, 7:30am - 8:30am
Where: 18th Amendment Spirits, Co. 350 W. Western in downtown Muskegon
How much: There will be no charge for breakfast but healthy donations are welcome.
What’s for breakfast: Catered by Ryke’s

post_text: Good things to remember this spring at the soccer fields and all of our athletic fields and facilities!
shared_text:
Reeths-Puffer Youth Soccer
April 9, 2018 at 12:26 PM ·

As we look forward to starting full practices this week (positive thoughts for the weather) a few reminders to share with all who will be at the fields this season:
No smoking on the fields or within the parking lots. This is a school policy and we are occupying their space.
No dogs on the fields during practice times or games. This includes old dogs, young dogs, big dogs, and little dogs.
Please throw trash in trash bins. We have them staggered around the facility.
We do have a lost and found. So if you misplace something check in with us at the clubhouse it may have been returned here.
Playing is for the kids. Spectating is for the families and friends. Coaching is for the coaches.
Please have a whole lot of fun this Spring and cheer enthusiastically for ALL players.
1-2-3 LET'S GO RPYSC!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

post_text: This is how you launch Rocketoons in a new county! A huge and happy Rocket City welcome to Berrien County!!! We officially launched our Rocketoons in Berrien County on Friday, March 16th with the help of Laurie Marszalec's 4th graders at Lake Michigan Catholic Elementary. Rocketoons in Berrien County are brought to you by Lory's Place, under the direction of the wonderful and talented Stephanie Kohler (seen here in one of her more serious moments). Rocketoons are free, Rocketoons are designed to help kids talk about the stress in their lives, and Rocketoons are now up and running in Berrien County. Tell your friends, tell your neighbors, watch Rocketoons when you're supposed to be working on that report for the CFO. Rocketoons.com. Enjoy!

Rocketoons are free, Rocketoons are designed to help kids talk about the stress in their lives, and Rocketoons are now up and running in Berrien County. Tell your friends, tell your neighbors, watch Rocketoons when you're supposed to be working on that report for the CFO. Rocketoons.com. Enjoy!

post_text:
I'd say it's about time for a Teacher Feature - wouldn't you? Say hello to RPEL's Alecia Hernandez.

1. What was your favorite subject/project as a student?
My favorite subject as a student was math.

2. What is your favorite subject/project as a teacher/administrator?
As a teacher I continue to love math and watch my students explore different ways to work through problems.

3. Where did you go to college, and what did you study?
I went to college at Grand Valley State University and studied English/language Arts with a minor in Elementary Education.

4. What is your favorite quote?
Enjoy the little things in life, for one day you'll look back and realize they were the big things.

post_text:
Let's check the calendar, shall we? Yep, it's Teacher Feature Friday! Meet RPMS PE teacher, Andy Brown.

1. What was your favorite subject/project as a student?
My favorite subject was advanced PE. It was the first time where I challenged my mind and body in the same class. I was amazed at the fact I could set goals and reach them and record my work.

2. What is your favorite subject/project as a teacher/administrator?
I love my navigating life class. I feel like I get an opportunity to change their lives and share experiences I had growing up and also get an opportunity to hear about their life both at school and out of school.

3. Where did you go to college, and what did you study?
I graduated from Grand Valley State University where I was a Physical Education major.

4. What is your favorite quote?
"Those that think they can and those who think they cant are both right. Strive for greatness."
